   <abstract>This large map on four sheets depicts the lands of the University of the South at Sewanee, basically the geological and topographical features prior to the construction of the campus. Sewanee Company's Railroad, the Nashville and Chattanooga Railroad (incl. the Cowan Tunnel), and various roads, creeks, and "chalybeate" (iron-bearing mineral) springs are shown. Relief shown by hachures. Includes a geological section from the Mississippi, through Nashville and Knoxville, to the Warm Springs in North Carolina.</abstract>
   <abstract>Sewanee: the University of the South was founded in 1857 as an Episcopalian college. Led by Leonidas Polk and funded by John Armfield, various southern dioceses collaborated to create this school on the Cumberland Plateau in Franklin County. During the Civil War, the cornerstone was destroyed by Union soldiers. Contruction resumed following the war and the school finally opened in 1868.</abstract>
